===from:Lindsay Bowie
===email:lindsaybowie@yahoo.com
===date:Thu Feb 27  9:51:57 2003
===subject:Chapter 8 Discussion
===message:Anticommunism dominated the Truman administration's agenda and was the main focus of political battles for presdiency.  Anticommunism was conformed to by the government and each side fought to be the primary advocate for it.  Television, magazines, and newspapers covered anticommunist topics daily and encouraged Americans to support anticommunist ideas.  The government made decisions to seek out informants and spies and charge them with espionage and treason.  Not all acts of the government were supported by evidence, especially those acts of Joe McCarthy, but the hysteria of Americans had risen so quickly and so greatly that no one dared to speak negatively about the government's actions for fear of being punished themselves.  The government set examples of what they would do to pro-communists through the execution of the Rosenberg's and through dramatically sifting through and terminating government employees on a regular basis.  McCarthyism was supported greatly by all Americans for fear of the consequences if they did not support it.  I feel that Americans are so prone to hysteria because the government creates it in a lot of cases.  For instance, our government is now encouraging us to buy plastic sheeting and duct tape to cover our homes in case of germ warfare.  To my surprise, a lot of people are doing it!  I feel that if it is going to happen, there's not a whole lot that plastic and tape can do to prevent us from either getting sick or dying.  We cannot live in our homes in fear on a daily basis.  We were shocked by the events of 9/11 and the government has now decided that since Americans were so angry about what happened on 9/11, they must go that extra mile to be sure they are not blamed for another catastrophy.  We are a nation rallied to fight terrorism and war, but we're having to fight a war within our own country just to feel safe.  
=========yorg=========
===from:Robert Napier
===date:Wed Mar 12  5:00:22 2003
===subject:Chapter 8 Discussion
===message:Several factors contributed to the anticommunist hysteria that swept the United States. First, American politics played the major role, because they convinced people that communism was running rampant world wide and they needed to get control of the situation or it would take over in the states. Second, Russia, a communist nation, was gaining power and this movement concerned the United States deeply, because they worried that Russia would get too powerful and destroy America. McCarthyism received so much attention; because he convinced people that communism was still running rampant. He spoke out against Truman and the government to no end and people started to listen to what McCarthy was saying. We want our children to live in a country that is safe and when the cause is put into jeopardy, we go into a panic. 
=========yorg=========
===from:Kathryn D. Hambrick-Mateen
===email:kathryns@bellsouth.net
===date:Fri Mar 21  6:52:49 2003
===subject:Hysteria in America
===message:Americans believed that our country had been infiltrated by  teason and subversion which they contributed to the cause of foreign difficulties. They were angry with the executive administration for not being aggressive enough to prevent China from becoming communist,and the fact that the Soviets had built and exploded their own atomic bomb only increased fear in Americans. Americans had been through a lot,and after World War II they were suspicious of any New Deal purposed, they believe it to be a communist plot to sovietize America. Anyone who acted, talked, thought,or associated with certain groups were classified as communist,and if one was simpatheic toward civil rights, your affiliation was questionable. The Cold War caused legitmate concerns about American security. When the discovery of communistic agents working in the Federal government president Truman mandated the "Truman Doctrine" establishing the Federal Employee Loyalty Program to root out subversives in government service. The revelation of the Hollywood 10, the Hiss, Rosenbergs,Fuch,and others communist episodes struck panic at home. Americans didn't know who to trust,so when Republican Senator McCarthy started his rebell rousing everyone got on the band wagon. He was making the kind of noise Americans wanted to hear.McCarthys accusations of communist weren't valid in most cases, nor did he produce evidence to support his finger pointing,it was totally a political diversion to enhance his potential political career, at the same time putting down the current administration in office. 
As far as the post 911 ordeal,and duck tape thing I am clueless, because if something is going to happen in a America be it physical destruction or germ warfare what type of protection can one get from DUCK TAPE?
=========yorg=========
===from:Kevin Tyler
===date:Fri Mar 21 14:24:43 2003
===subject:discussion
===message:The contributing factor of the anticommunism hysteria was the emergence of Russia as a legitimate "Super Power".  Going straight to the bottom line President Truman and Stalin were involved in a major pee contest and their fear/dislike or unwillingness to coexist filtered down to the American people.  The spread of communism was a major threat to the democratic government of the U.S. and being associated with communisim was viewed as assisting the enemy.  A legitimate threat leads to fear, fear leads to hatred, hatred produces hysteria.  For example if the weather forcast calls for a major snow storm in Georgia you will not be able to find a gallon of milk or a loaf of bread in the metro area.  Just as our current state of hysteria, out of the fear of biological warfare the consumption of duct tape and plastic is off the scale.  Americans are so prone to panic because of fear.  That same fear is what makes people naturally believe the worst case scenerio.    
=========yorg=========
===from:Chris Schmidt
===email:chris@d2dtech.com
===date:Sat Mar 22  9:42:10 2003
===subject:Anti-communism in the mid century
===message:<p>The end of World War II left communist Russia is a position of increased power and in possesion of a vastly increased sphere of influence that the Allies were in a bad position to combat. Our European allies were wrecked militarily and Americans just wanted the troops to come home. As the Soviets defied the international community establishing puppet regimes, Americans realized the growing threat of an agressive, expansionist Russian global presense. When the Soviets detinated an Atomic bomb, the real terror in America began.</p>
<p>With the uncovering of a communist spy ring that handed over atomic secrets to our cold war adversary, there was legitimate reason to battle espionage, but the ferver spread beyond simply espionage and subversion to an idealist witch hunt for anyone who leaned too far too the left. Senator McArthy stoked the fires for political gain as did other hard line Republicans. The result was a public in open panic of communist infiltrators, and the government trampling of Constiutional rights was ignored by a populace in mortal fear.</p>
<p>I think the current political climate bears numerous differences than the communist scare. The population is not in a complete panic and fright of foreign terrorism. The potential is there, but we have not yet gone that far down the road to repression. I think Americans currently see the reasons for vigilance, but also see that we are capable of protecting ourselves. I don't see fear of terrorism as comperable to the rampant fear of communism as an almost unstoppable force of global domination. Of course there are always extreme people who are easily driven to panic, but my household is secure in the knowledge that we are more likely to be involved in a car wreck than a terrorist attack. We wear our seatbelts, but don't own any gas masks. Our cars have airbags, but we like the nice spring air too much to put plastic on the windows.</p>
=========yorg=========
===from:Carla Foster
===date:Sat Mar 22 16:55:50 2003
===subject:Chapter 8 Discussion
===message:The causes of the anticommunist hysteria were the Chinese communists takeover of China, Soviets exploding their own atomic bomb, and the U.S. political campaign.  When China became the People's Republic of China, it signified that U.S. efforts to stop communism failed.  When the Soviets exploded its own atomic bomb, it signified its determination to flex its power and maybe transmit some fear in the U.S.  However, when the U.S. government examined its own administration for any disloyalty and proclaim a campaign againist communism, anticommunism hysteria swept the nation (HUAC investigations; many states enacted antisubversion laws and loyalty programs).  McCarthyism received so much support because it was appealing and Americans believed or wanted to believe that the country's foreign difficulties were to due to treason.  Americans are prone to panic because of fear and because its created by our government and media.  To suggest that we go out and buy duct tape and plastic sheeting to protect ourselves against biological warfare just doesn't make sense.  Although these items would not be defense, many individuals did go out and buy the materials and believe they are life-saving items.
=========yorg=========
===from:Kristi Smith
===date:Sat Mar 22 17:36:31 2003
===subject:Chpt 8 discussion
===message:I feel the causes of the anticommunist hysteria could be linked to the quick enforcement of communism in certain countries (mainly Poland) and the announcement that Russia also had an atomic bomb and then also an h-bomb.  The American people could not figure out why its government was having a hard time keeping Stalin under some sort of control.  The introduction of possible multiple spy networks, one in the U.S. and one in Canada, did nothing but feed the fear of the American people.  McCarthyism received support because these fears had finally been realized.  The Federal Employee Loyalty Program brought on a whole new look at things for the people.  The loosely lead program immediately started forcing the resignation of employees for things as simple as having a friend of a friend of a friend that was a little suspicious.  The public as a whole only saw that thousands government employees were forced to resign, meaning, in their eyes, there was a major problem with Democratic leadership of the country.  I think that one major reason Americans are prone to panic is the feeling that we are bound to be attacked.  I have heard from numerous people that until 9/11, America had really been “lucky” in escaping the terrorist of so many other countries.  Once 9/11 happened, these same people felt like if it happened once, it would happen again; hence the reason for the mad dash to the store for duct tape and plastic.  The United States of America has been seen for decades as the dominating force of the world, why wouldn’t some egotistical country want to try to take control of that title?
=========yorg=========
===from:Kathryn Hatch
===date:Sat Mar 22 19:55:28 2003
===subject:Chapter 8
===message:I believe the extreme anticommunist movement of the Cold War era and the fear of terrorism post-9/11 share one important aspect in common - the fear that bad things can happen here on American soil.  Americans in the 40s were scared of the H-bomb and Americans in the new millenium are scared of airplanes and germ warfare attacks.  Additionally, the fear in the 40s that a communist might live next door is similar to the fear these days that the guy sitting next to you on the plane might try to hijack it.  In America we enjoy very comfortable living and, compared to the rest of the world, a secure and safe lifestyle...when we feel that is threatened, it's something that rightfully calls for our attention and frightens us.
=========yorg=========
===from:Connie Plowden
===date:Sat Mar 22 20:26:23 2003
