===subject:from snowball to avalanche
===message:The causes of the anticommunist hysteria that swept the nation in the late 1940s and early 1950s were nothing more than finger pointing, hatred, and ignorance.  Following WWII Americans feared any threat to freedom whether it be found in an atomic bomb in Russia, a communist China or the unsubstantial fears of the uninformed American.  McCarthyism received so much attention because people were afraid and didnt know who to trust or listen to.  It is convenient that senator McCarthy appeared with all the answers and the enlightened knowledge of who in America was communist, I say this jokingly of course.  Americans love to panic.  But more than panic, Americans like to feel like they have control over the situation.  Much like during the Cuban missile crisis, American children were told that if a missile hits, get under your desk and cover your head.  Im no balistics expert, but something tells me that if a missile hits, crawling under my desk and covering my head is not going to save me.  It is almost in the way that it mirrors the idea of duct tape and plastic sheeting saving me from biochem warfare.  Again im no expert, but this is utterly ridiculous.  Another example of panic, was post 9/11 and the fear of getting in an airplane.  Terrorism, is just that, the infliction of terror.  So by not getting in an airplane, terrorism was affecting you and not the other way around.  
=========yorg=========
===from:Vickie Saunders
===date:Mon Mar 24 16:27:12 2003
===subject:Chapter 8
===message:The causes of anticommunism hysteria that swept that nation during the 1940’s and 1950’s was the Cold War evolving, the Red Scare of World War II, the establishment of the House Committee on Un-American Activities. 

The reason why McCarthyism received so much support is because he informed his fellow Republicans that the Democrats were being too easy on the communists. When he filed a suit against several women he thought were communists after attending a GOP meeting West Virginia, his effort to prove that communism existed in the GOP, gained support of many Americans. 

Americans are so prone to panic because we live in a country where our government is unjust and dishonest and a time where the possibility of any type of threat on our soil is unimagined and unrealized. The Civil War and the Pearl Harbor attacks are the last major incidents on our soil the effects of both have been long forgotten by the average American. This is why such panic arose when the September 11th attacks happened.  So many Americans stopped going to work, took their children out of school, bought enormous amounts of groceries and supplies from the store until they thought is was safe again. Also when the government informed the public of the possible threat of biological weapons from terrorists and made suggestions to prevent infection, Americans bought massive quantities of duct tape and plastic sheeting.

=========yorg=========
===from:Ursula Davis
===date:Mon Mar 24 20:44:45 2003
===subject:Chapter 8 Discussion
===message:I think that the anticommunist hysteria of the 1940's and early 1950's was able to go on because of the backing of the government.  Russia, who was the enemy, was communist so anything communist obviously was also the enemy.  By placing this idea and fear of domination by communism into the American people, different government officals were able to gain trust and backing including the President.  People like to feel that they are being looked after and protected, as well as wanting to protect.  President Truman portrayed himself as a protector of the free world thereby a protector of the American people.  Others like McCarty were able to exploit this panic and hysteria to their advantage by pointing a finger at others to gain confidence and support from people.  You were either with McCarty, or you were a communist.  Being a communist meant, fines, jail, unemployment, even death.  Being loyal meant prosperity.  Which would you choose.  It seems very similar to mafia tactics of paying for protection.  American seem very prone to panic based on a mass paranoia.  When something bad happens like the threat of war, Russia matching America's atomic and hydrogen bombs, China taken over by a Communist power, we panic.  The fact that there were indeed some Americans who sympathized with the communist ideology and some spys and traiters to the U.S only served to fuel the fire for those in government who wanted to get ahead.  I have worked for the state for the past ten and a half years.  About two months ago my office mailed out a form to be signed and sent back in.  Upon reading the form and the State Constitutions citing it was from, I discovered firsthand that Georgia is one of the states that requires it's federal and state employees to sign an Oath the State and U.S. Constitutions.  After ten years, I think it's a bit late and I was very insulted.  Coworkers of mine felt that it really made no differnce to them as long as they continued to get a paycheck.  Now I see where this bit of legislature came from and I am very upset at having to sign it.  Obviously, the effects of 9/11/01 and the possibility of War with Iraq spurred this new resurgence of signing this oath.  Working full time, attending school and raising a family really puts me out of the loop sometimes because I was totally confused when I went to Walmart about a month ago and saw everyone in line with water, duct tape, and plastic.  I asked my husband who is an ex-marine( if there is such a thing) and army man why everyone was purchasing these items.  He told me that it was mass hysteria and the idea that covering your home with the plastic sheeting and duck tape would keep out chemical warfare.  He also told me that this was nonsense and would not work.  Since he was in the Desert Storm operation, I tended to listen to him.  The "fight or flight" reaction is in our nature as human beings.  Any signs of possible danger, puts us in a state of panic.  Unfortunately, sometimes the media and unscrupulous people in buisnesses and even government play on that fear in order to lead us in the desired directions or take advantage of us for their own gains.
=========yorg=========
===from:Brenda Miller
===date:Mon Mar 24 21:02:26 2003
===subject:Ch 8 discussion
===message:The cause of anticommunist hysteria was the fear of the unknown.  It seemed that the communistist were unreasonable people determined to rule many lands.  The American government used this fear of the unknown to gain support of the American people to drive the government to become stronger with fewer restrictions than were previously in place.  For instance, the fear of communists allowed for government investigations to be allowed to run rampant.   McCarthyism received support because McCarthy seemed to be trying to inform the American public about things the government was trying to hide, he seemed to play upon the true blue American spirit.  Americans are prone to panic because we feel powerless to defend ourselves as individuals.  We have never before had to realisiticaly worry about invaisions in our homes and communities.  After 9/11 our nation suffered in the aftermath of the knowledge that people really do hate us and that we are not as safe as we once believed.  Most of us are used to an ideal life (in comparision to other countries, not our ultra rich and powerful) where few are hungry and homeless and at the hands of rebel forces.  We are used to being the defenders of others, not a country who is preparing for possible attack.  Terror alerts and duct tape/plastic sheeting are new ideas for us and our panic is out of the fear of the unknown.
=========yorg=========
===from:Lucille Clayton
===institution:HIST 2110
===date:Mon Mar 24 21:17:09 2003
===subject:Chapter 8 Discussion Question
===message:Stalin's refusal to abandon dominance in Eastern Europe was matched by Truman's unwillingness to concede Soviet supremacy beyond Russia's own borders.  Truman administration felt that the right of nations to self-determination, a betrayal of democratic principles, and a cover for the spread of communism were all possible if  Stalin was not stopped.  Much of McCarthy's support came from our elected officials that applauded him for telling lies and getting the American people stirred up.  He helped to uproot several Democractic seats, just like our recent elections.  He caused commotion within the American people that flawed up prejudices from one class against another.  Americans tend to listen to the elected officials that we have voted into office.  We believe that they truly have our best interest at heart.  Whether or not they had a personal gain in sending 50% of Americans into the hardware stores for duct tape and plastic, I don't know.  I think sometimes the government sends Americans on a wild goose chase, just to see if they still have control of us.  This sounds rather communistic to me.
=========yorg=========
===from:Andrew Bell
===email:csu12497@mail.claytonstate.net
===date:Mon Mar 24 21:25:10 2003
===subject:Panic?  Why Panic?
===message:It seems as though Americans always jump to conclusions.  Right now CNN is exploiting the war and beefing everything up for the public.  The anti-communism was an example of Americans wanting some type of retribution here at home.  When there is nobody to blame for something, you look for someone to blame.  It is the old gang up on the person that can't defend themselves routine.  Humans love to be lead.  It is a common fact that most people jump on to the bandwagon without even knowing where that bandwagon is going.  The same thing is true with the anti-communism.  Make up some hearings, call some people communists, and watch the American public revel in all the glory of catching a so called communist.  After 9/11 it took a long while to get things back to normal in our homeland.  Panic is just a common reaction from people that think they are invisible to suck attacks.  9/11 opened our eyes and made us realize that we are susceptible to being attacked.  Thus, we all had a little bit of panic in the back of our minds.  It is hard not to panic when CNN is running 24 hour coverage of the same "propaganda" over and over.



=========yorg=========
===from:Sharon Stanley
===date:Mon Mar 24 21:56:38 2003
===subject:Ch 8 Discussion
===message:We tend to fear what we don't understand.  I think that this is part of why we are so prone to panic. It was quite easy to blame the Russians for some our war woes - didn't they break several promises to us?  Because they were against democracy and all things that were held dear by Americans they were considered a threat.  We certainly wouldn't want to be drawn into another war.  They would have to be stopped!  Unfortunately all of the propoganda of the time (including McCarthyism) likely gave Americans a biased view of the Russians.  This is in no way meant to say that the Russians were simply misunderstood.  However if we fear the unknown, then Russia was certainly bound to cause mistrust. We are a very patriotic country.  This means that we tend to hop on any bandwagon with a God Bless America bumper sticker.  While this is not always a bad thing we must always investigate issues for ourselves.  Consider the issue of people buying mass quantities of duct tape and plastic sheeting.  If chemical warfare uses gasses that are odorless and colorless, then how do we know when to cover our windows.  And what do we do once we run out of air in our sealed homes?  For that matter when do don our gas masks.  The name of the game is information.  Not the bombardment that we have now.  Every television channel and radio station has constant "up to the minute" updates on the war.  I believe this fuels some of the mass panic that we seem to be prone to. While chemical warfare is a very real possibility/danger, we need to stop and think and quit buying into the gloom and doom being broadcast at us. We do indeed live in perilous times but will we stop living or worse yet live in fear for the remainder of our lives?
=========yorg=========
===from:LINDA DAWSON
===date:Mon Mar 24 22:11:12 2003
===subject:HIST 2110
===message:During the 1940s and 1950s, the United States enjoyed prosperity from economic development and nucleur development of the atomic bomb. The aggression by the USSR and its will to exact its communist beliefs throughout Europe and parts of Asia caused a widespread mistrust of communism. Also, the creation of the atomic and hydrogen bombs by the Soviet Union further deepened the mistrust of the communist state because the United States no longer had supreme dominancy over the world. McCarthyism received a lot of support because the people of the U.S. were afraid of being accused of being communist and being blacklisted. Americans are prone to panic because we are afraid of being taken away from our comfort zones and when a traumatic incident occurs within this country (as in 9/11) it propels the American people to fear the propaganda that is exploited by the media and some leaders. This can be related to when the Americans during this timeframe conducted nuclear bomb drills and the creation of bomb shelters.
=========yorg=========
