===from:Michael E. Elbe
===email:csu16286@mail.claytonstate.net
===date:Mon Mar 24 22:22:04 2003
===subject:Ch. 8 Disc.
===message:Fears of the spread of communism around the world helped cause the “Red Scare” after WWII just as it had after WWI.  Also, increasing tensions between the Soviet Union and the West, specifically America, helped to further fan the flames of anticommunist hysteria.  McCarthyism received enormous support because it fed on people’s existing fears about communism.  The people of America went on a search for anyone who they thought might be communist because they feared these people would try to overthrow the government.  I think Americans are prone to panic because we are somewhat isolated from the world by the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.  We share the longest undefended border in the world with Canada and are on good terms with Mexico.  This gives us an unusual sense of security, and whenever that security is threatened we tend to overreact to it.  We are so grateful for what we have we don’t want anything to take it from us.  Since the acts of 9/11/01 we have become increasingly suspicious of anything and anyone that might harm us again.  We also go to almost ridiculous lengths to protect ourselves.  In the 1950’s it was backyard bomb shelters and last month it was the duct tape and plastic wrap.  If you look at areas of the world who deal with insecurity on a daily basis (like Israel) you will see that they are much more prepared because threats to their security occur on a daily basis.
=========yorg=========
===from:Chad-Everett Tisdale
===date:Mon Mar 24 22:39:38 2003
===subject:its the media's fault
===message:I am going to have to jump on the bandwagon and blame the media for the easiness of Americans to be so fooled into paranoia.  Actually, I would have to explain that the media gives us images of death and destruction and Hollywood gives us the movies that support these ideas and we watch them.  So, indirectly, Americans are at fault for their own paranoia.  Gossip has always been such a detrimental thing.  I believe that individuals are capable of making rash decisions but people, as a collective are very prone to panic.  I am glad that the Government gives us the ideas of taping our windows and other such things but if only there was a way to pass on the information without everyone freaking out.  We all have such a mistrust of our neighbor that we will take the smallest evidence of anything amiss and jump to conclusions.  Once again I think that the media capitalizes on this with such movies as Conspiracy Theory, and Enemy of the State.
=========yorg=========
