===from:Hannah Terrence
===date:Mon Mar 24 23:23:38 2003
===subject:Discussion 8
===message:When people fail to educate themselves, they rely on leadership to think for them instead. And leaders can control the masses fairly easily with superstition. Duct tape and plastic sheeting? A classic illustration. Many Americans didn't stop to ask some very simple questions about that little idea. These items do come in handy in a concrete apartment in Israel if you do not have the money to install a professional safe room. And it is used in biological/viral hot zones to repair biological space suits. But the average American could not easily seal every crack in their home with these materials. The leaders in the 50's were master manipulators of mass hysteria in our nation. The atomic bomb blew our collective mind, and we collectively went insane for a while, much like we are in danger of doing now, I think. 9/11 changed me as an individual of course, and shook my sense of safety to the core. And I have made changes. I no longer allow my son to fly alone. I have yet to see acceptable lasting change in security measures for air passengers. It may or may not be the right thing, but it's a decision I make for myself and for him, reviewing information I carefully gather. I did not buy plastic and duct tape. I have wood floors and a crawl space under my house, it wouldn't seal it. And statistically, I'm unlikely to be affected by such an attack. Emergency stash? I've maintained a system for that since I went through Hurricane Andrew. I didn't need my government to help me make any of these decisions. I have a strong inherent distrust of any government who employs tactics of mass hysteria, rather than encouraging people to think for themselves. I'll mandate my own reality, thanks, and I hope I won't get arrested for it someday. I'm not famous enough yet to be blacklisted.        
=========yorg=========
